== Japanese content ==
{{出典の明記|date=2020年9月}}
This article treats '''Kumano Shrine''' (くまのじんじゃ) in {{ill|lt=Takashima|Q845794|qid=Q845794|1=Takashima, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|qid=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}, which is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}. Although named Kumano Shrine, there is also a tradition that it is unrelated to the so-called {{ill|lt=Kumano Sanzan|Q10403700|qid=Q10403700|1=Kumano Three Shrines}}.

Formerly, three major routes ran north-south through Takashima District: the Hokurikudō (Nishi-Ōmi road), Akatsuki (Meigetsu) road, and Saba road. Of these, the Meigetsu road ran across Kumano-yama (today's Aibano upland). It is said Oda Nobunaga used this road during his campaign against the Asakura.

Local priestly-family documents (e.g., ''Furumiya Family Documents,'' ''Aiba Family Documents'') record that "the shikinaisha Kumano Shrine originally stood at Nos e in Kumano-yama along Meigetsu road; on March 16, Genki 3, it was burned by Mori Hanbei Tame-mura, and residents moved the sacred symbol into the precinct of {{ill|lt=Harifu Shrine|Q11555577|qid=Q11555577|1=Hanifu Shrine}}." The old site name Mikoshi-daira remains, but it is now within a Self-Defense Force training area and inaccessible.

At the former south end (Koga village) and north end (Nishino village) of Meigetsu road were remote worship sites of Kumano Shrine; these correspond to the present Kumano Shrines at Kamikoga in Azumigawa-chō and at Oi in Imazu-chō.

